Rather than adding this here (and the check to configure), I think you can replace the `dprintf` call completely.  There are only two calls and they are down around line 238 of this file:

```
   if (si) {
     dprintf(STDERR_FILENO,
         "Terminating due to signal %d %s "	
         "generated by pid=%d uid=%d. %s (%p)\n",
         signo, w_strsignal(signo), si->si_pid, si->si_uid,
         reason, si->si_value.sival_ptr);
   } else {	
     dprintf(STDERR_FILENO, "Terminating due to signal %d %s. %s\n",	  
       signo, w_strsignal(signo), reason);	    
   }	  
```

Can be replaced with something like:

```
if (si) {
  auto msg = watchman::to<std::string>(
        "Terminating due to signal ", signo, " ", w_strsignal(signo),
         " generated by pid=", si->si_pid, " uid=", si->si_uid,  " ",
         reason, " (", si->si_value.sival_ptr, ")\n");
  ignore_result(write(fd, msg.data(), msg.size()));
} else {
auto msg = watchman::to<std::string>(
        "Terminating due to signal ", signo, " ", w_strsignal(signo),
         " ", reason, "\n")
  ignore_result(write(fd, msg.data(), msg.size()));
}
```

@hvelarde no please!! 😄 Keep the parenthesis on its own, for two reasons:

- there is a clear clue where the statement finishes (as it will be aligned with the ``t`` of target
- if eventually someone needs to add a second parameter the diff will be just one single line, rather than two

for a start, we can wrap this in a try-except, and set a status code on the span. i bet this will give us something close to what we want:

```
from elasticsearch.exceptions import Transport Error
....
try:
    result = super(TracedTransport, self).perform_request(method, url, params=params, body=body)
except TransportError as e:
    s.set_tag(http.STATUS_CODE, e.status_code)
    raise
```

@drjova `invenio-search-ui` is by default registered on different Flask instance.

- `app` - "standard application" (`/login`, `/search`, ...)
- `api_app` - contains all REST-API endpoint with custom exception handling (`/api/...`)

@gbordyugov yes technically the check for ```None``` is redundant, but I would argue that we need this repetition to have clearer error message for easier debugging.

If its ```None```, we know the error is there is no data provided.
If its wrongly typed, we have different message indicating it.

