@jwhui and I looked at the Thread spec about the PSKd and found it to be rather underspecified.

We'd prefer this be the base-32 encoded string be used here instead of the "binary data" representation (which is underspecified). That way we can clarify with the Thread Group and correct the problem in the NCP. It also makes the API more straightforward.

That would mean the packed-encoding would be `A(t(ULE))`.

@bukepo, I am not sure what your suggestion is... 
- In the first version of this PR the method signature was `InvalidateCacheEntry(Cache &aEntry, const char * aReason)`  instead of `InvalidateCacheEntry(Cache &aEntry, InvalidationReason aReason)`. See comments above about this.
- In current version, if the log is not enabled, method `ConvertInvalidationReasonToString()` is not used and should be removed by linker.

the problem is, that `__slots__` don't guarantee the existence of an `attribute`, i.e. see this error:

```
    def __eq__(self, other):
        if isinstance(other, TargetState):
            return (
                self.our_address == other.our_address and
                self.from_route == other.from_route and
                self.from_transfer == other.from_transfer and
                self.block_number == other.block_number and
>               self.secret == other.secret and
                self.state == other.state
            )
E           AttributeError: secret

raiden/transfer/mediated_transfer/state.py:169: AttributeError
```

I agree with the "generic" way being complex, but I would argue that adding specific `hasattr` checks for all `__slots__` by name isn't much less complex/difficult to read?

Would you be more comfortable with defining
```
def safe_equal_attribute_value(attribute, self, other):
  if hasattr(self, attribute) and hasattr(other, attribute):
    return self.__getattribute__(attribute) == other.__getattribute__(attribute)
  else:
    return not hasattr(self, attribute) and not hasattr(other, attribute)
```
and calling `safe_equal_attribute_value` on all defined slots specifically?

Or do you have a better suggestion?
